review: it would've been stupid to trash
review_word: so, these are the SECOND Bushnell Powerview 16 x 50 binoculars...right? they BOTH had double vision! On the first pair, I trashed them...my stupidity (well...if the warranty was true, it would've been stupid to trash..but...read on)...so I buy a second pair later on....they have double vision...so this time I pull out my binoc folder...see that it has a "lifetime warranty"..call Bushnell, spoke to "Travis", explained all...he says well, if you still had the first ones, you could've returned them to us...so I said, well I have the second ones...so...per his instructions and direction, I returned the binocs (I had to pay $14 shippping)...because I was informed that Bushnell would either 1. repair or 2. replace.....After a month's time, I receive a letter from them saying they couldn't repair, but they would "offer" me another pair for "only" $56.61..right? THAT was $25 MORE than what I had originally paid for these worthless things....so, I called Bushnell, once AGAIN....repeated my conversation originally with "Travis"....the Bushnell rep tells me they found "dirt and leaves" inside the lens...ok..."WHAT"? We are not hunters...we are not campers...I know they don't know this...but honestly, neither of these two binocs had ever left my "shoulder"....I am convinced they are not honoring their warranties...so...I'm out a pair of binnocs I've paid for twice, plus the $14 shipping....NEVER...NEVER buy these...don't know where the 3,4 or more "star reviews" come from...but this is an honest one!

review: “It’s not about treasure, it’s about history!”
review_word:
In a dig site of a no-name tomb, something is unleashed and three people go to pieces. The tomb is sealed again and decades later it is reopened by a team wearing hazmat suits. A hanging coffin is discovered along with a fancy necklace. The coffin is brought to London for all to see, except for the poor man who is killed for his eyes. After that, bodies begin to pile up at an alarming rate. Time is short. The evil mummy Talos must collect all of his body parts before the planets align. He accomplishes this goal as litter, a trail of rags, dirty old wrapping.

This movie is noted for wasting the considerable talents of Christopher Lee and Honor Blackman in fragmented scenes lasting but a few seconds each. Shelley Duvall shows up late to the massacre while Gerard Butler slips out early, probably glad to be out of it. The only one who appears to be having any fun is Sean Pertwee. Otherwise, it offers nothing new to the mummy genre. It is passable entertainment at best.

This is a film about a dystopian future in which the government is ruled by the military, and uses the television to control the masses. There is no such thing as free journalism, as everything seen on news broadcasts is freely edited to say what the government wants it to say. Arnold Schwarzenegger stars as a policeman who falls victim to the bureaucracy when he refuses to fire on a group of rioters, and finds himself in prison for a crime he is innocent of. He makes a break for freedom, only to be recaptured and become a contestant on a game show called "The Running Man," which is a bloodthirsty farce of justice that has convicted felons running for their lives from so-called Stalkers, who are nothing but psychopaths that just happen to work for the government, all broadcast live on television for the ravenous fans. Joining him is Maria Conchita Alonso as the citizen that turned him in, and two revolutionaries played by Yaphet Kotto and Jim Brown. This was a film late in Schwarzenegger's career, so it makes use of some of his catchphrase lines such as "I'll be back," and has the usual blend of violence and humor that his movies were known for. But, with Richard Dawson guest starring as the game show host who is responsible for sending men to their deaths at the hands of a pack of killers, it has a certain charm and is entertaining, if somewhat predictable.

review: Brilliant Subplots With Fabulous Interwoven Ending -- Perfect for at home Movie Night
review_word:
For the first half of this movie I thought I was watching numerous, independent storylines. Then the ending brought all these brilliant subplots together, creatively linking various foreshadowing comments and scenes into a holistic story.

I was enticed to watch this by the great collection of actors and actress (many of whom are seen before the peaks of their individual stardoms in this 1998 film) including Gillian Anderson Angelina Jolie, Jay Mohr, and Ryan Philippe. They are accompanied by Hollywood standouts Sean Connery, Gena Rowlands, Ellen Burstyn, Madeleine Stowe, and Dennis Quaid. And as a bonus, Jon Stewart has a significant role, showing that he is much more than a talk show host.

It's a perfect film for an at home Movie Night, for couples, singles, and friends.

review: The Best Of Bob Dylan's Early Period
review_word: The first compilation album by Bob Dylan is the best way to indulge on his best classics whether it's acoustic or electric. The lead off track here is the same as Blonde On Blonde-"Rainy Day Women #12 & 35", which is great for the party-goers. This is followed by three of Dylan's "folk" classics-"Blowin' In The Wind"; "The Times They Are A-Changin'" and "It Ain't Me, Babe". The crown-achieving "Like A Rolling Stone" is his greatest rock piece and the first song to break the two-minute barrier single-wise. The original acoustic "Mr. Tambourine Man" leads off the second half of this set before the Byrds electrified it and took it to the top as their maiden voyage single release and the title of their debut album from 1965 which was the same year Dylan himself went electric at the Newport Folk Festival with two albums under his belt such as Bringing It All Back Home and Highway 61 Revisited. Speaking of the former album, it not only gave us the song just mentioned but also "Subterranean Homesick Blues" patterned after the Chuck Berry song "Too Much Monkey Business" which also serves as a stepping stone for Rap enthusiasts[Just kidding]. The second of three Blonde On Blonde songs here is "I Want You" with that never-ending guitar hook played by Nashville pro Wayne Moss. The song here previously released as a single only "Positively 4th Street", the follow-up to "Rolling Stone". Closing this first Dylan compilation album is the third song from Blonde On Blonde[and closing half of the first record of rock's first double album], "Just Like A Woman". Yes, every song on this album is a classic and yet most of these songs have widely been interpreted by many artists and even actors, i.e. William Shatner and Sebastian Cabot, the latter of whom had an album full of Bob Dylan songs in dramatic reading fashion. You could get more songs from the same period on his second greatest hits collection plus songs from the late '60s and early '70s. If you want a basic collection, this one is highly recommended and there would be no place that you're going to.

Safe As Milk is a timeless piece of music. It has the beatnik-styled poetry and randomly fascinating sense of style, cohesion, and innovation that all great art has. The band is great and captivating for nearly the entire album front to back. It may be the Beef's best album. That will depend on your own taste. It is certainly their most popular and endearing next to Trout Mask Replica. It is also one of the best albums of all time.

There is enough going on here for any music fan. There are anthems, rock outs, solos, good bass, and competent drums. And while not all of it is quite as crazy or innovative as some people tend to exaggerate, it is still the exhilarating and profound album that it was back in the 60s. Not much has changed. Pop music is a lot worse. But this kind of creativity powers on.

review: The best metal album ever made
review_word: The title is a bold statement, but in my humble opinion it is true. No album in the realm of metal is better than this one. Rob Halford's voice is at its absolute peak (and he was 40 years old when this album was recorded!), the guitar-work is absolutely phenomenal, and the drumming is simply mind-blowing. There is literally not a bad song on this album, hell there isn't even a good song, they're all beyond fantastic. It's simply pure perfection .The title track is probably the most iconic metal song ever recorded, I would say it's the pure definition of heavy metal. Hell Patrol and All Guns Blazing are just pure anthems of metal, Metal Meltdown is fast and thrashy as hell, and Leather Rebel is just such a fun song to listen to with it's rebellious spirit. A Touch of Evil is easily one of the best songs the band ever made, it has such a mysterious and evil vibe to it that you can't help but just bask in. The high notes that Rob hit towards the bridge to this song are simply mind-blowing. And then of course you have the epics Between the Hammer and the Anvil and Battle Hymn/One Shot at Glory, the latter song being my personal favorite Priest song. Overall, if you want to start someone out in the world of metal, or if you somehow haven't heard this album before, get this. It will seriously change your life.

Guilty was one of those albums that captured a special, if not, bittersweet, time in my life. Oh to be young and carefree, but subject to the pain that comes along with growing up. I was going through my Barbra phase, and her connection with the Bee Gees didn't hurt. This was one of my LPs on which there were so many good cuts; but, as I'm sure many of you have, one where you dropped the needle when needed. The title cut is so soulful. If I was a radio personality on an Old School R&B station, I'd have slip this one in and hope the music director didn't ding me for playing Barbra Streisand on a 'black' station. But, the cut was totally blue-eyed soul. Without giving you a cut by cut review of every selection on the album, I will say, the song that holds the deepest memory is 'The Love Inside'. I won't bore you with the events that lead to my returning home from a co-workers gathering where my heart my broken by the realization that 'it just wasn't gonna happen' because they brought someone else to the party... other than to say, I played this cut over and over and over.... and cried uncontrollably, until my brother came out of his bedroom (where he left his girlfriend) to ask me, "What the hell's wrong with you?" LOL... now. But, to this day, that song, while it doesn't register the same emotions of that night, still makes me stop and sigh. I'm sorry if I can't break down each cut on Guilty. But, listening to this classic is, after all this time, a guilty pleasure to me. Young people... meet Miss Barbra. She is, like butter.

item: Alice in Wonderland (Disney Gold Classic Collection)
review: Alice In Wonderland....not really my cup of tea, but my kids liked it!
review_word: I have a daughter who is curious about the Alice In Wonderland story & characters, so I thought this would be a good movie for us all to watch on family movie night. The DVDs themselves were in brand new perfect condition & played perfectly on our DVD/Blueray player, but the movie itself was not really one I could say I liked, the story itself was rather strange. I just don't understand what makes it such a classic since it doesn't really have much of a story itself...it just seems like a weird pointless dream Alice has & not really much else, but then again, I had never read the book Alice In Wonderland either, so maybe if I had read it before watching the movie, that might have made more sense to me, but I'm not so sure I want to...the way the characters interacted most of the time with each other in this movie seemed rather rude & negative. On the plus side, the movie itself was colorful, bright & clear as was the sound, and it kept both of my daughter's attention. There were some scenes in the movie they found amusing & made them laugh... they seemed to enjoy it, so that was good... they liked the characters of the Cheshire Cat & the White Rabbit best. I am giving it 3 stars because while I didn't really care for this particular movie, it kept my kids entertained & the DVDs themselves played perfectly. I am considering getting the movie version of AIW starring Johnny Depp....I really like him as an actor & maybe that one will be more enjoyable for me....although I will have to watch it first before I decide whether I will have my daughters watch it.

review: One of the best movie musicals ever, with great songs, and the pairing of Julie Andrews and Dick Van Dyke. A classic.
review_word: The Blu-ray definition is superior to the DVD and worth having, but a little grainy, and not as sharp as I would have liked, or have seen with other remastered films from the 60s. As for the movie itself, it is a classic, one of the best Hollywood musicals ever made, with wonderful music and lyrics by Sherman brothers Richard and Robert, and great performances by Julie Andrews, Dick Van Dyke (in multiple roles!), David Tomlinson (as Mr. Banks), and Glynis Johns. It also had Kris Kristofferson who played a far more intimidating mob boss than the 'voice' in this cut. The low end medical care scene, the mob boss's son, the boxing match, the kidnapping, Porter outwitting mob hitmen, the Porter being tortured scene and the drama at the end (are Kristofferson and his henchmen about to get Rosie the hooker and rescue the son?) have all been cut out of the director's cut. I also didn't care for the brutality Porter inflicted on his junkie wife in this remake.

I'd rate the theatrical release as a four star movie but could only give the director's cut two stars and that is being generous.

If you dig around online, you'll find mention that there is an issue with side D, specifically during "The Downward Spiral" and more obviously throughout "Hurt." I was hoping it wasn't the entire pressing that suffered, so I took a chance and ordered here. Unfortunately the copy I received from Amazon was defective. The record really sounds amazing until you get to the end and then a poor quality control led to a defective pressing. I checked it out using three different digital sources as a comparison and there's definitely a problem with this "Definitive Edition" vinyl that to my ear is in the left channel only, cutting in and out. It's a drag, because the album sounds great otherwise. To lose fidelity during "Hurt" makes it, uhh, hurt more? That's "new vinyl" for ya from a non-audiophile label these days.

review: Want to show off your system?
review_word: I very much appreciate the detailed reviews that discuss many of the great songs on this album. And the album is amazing. But this review is for those who not only love the music itself, but the sound quality. Particularly Little Wing. The song sounds good on a mediocre stereo system, and spectacularly impressive on a well put together one. Of course Stevie sounds wonderful, but the impact of the percussion and bass are stunning - particularly at relatively high volume. The great playing and engineering add up to a demo quality album that will impress!

review: Wins Again- Emotional, Dramatic, Inventive and Interesting
review_word:
If you ever wondered where the cultural phenomenon of the Rocky movies originated, Stallone makes it irreversibly clear with this stylish and charismatic film. Stallone's talent is staggering yet very easy to underestimate somehow as it becomes lost in the wholeness of the overwhelmingly entertaining and engagingly inspirational series. Stallone proves his worth as a Director once again and shows a lot of range with his well developed and extremely nuanced cast performances, which is the sign of great directing every time. Stallone manages to act, direct and pen this film with characteristic humor and depth while allowing us to glide through the preamble before a rousing end fight with predictable yet evocative results. It feels like a smaller film than some of the others but also more humanistic and sensitive. The missing performance of Talia Shire, the central character in Rocky's life 'Adrian' from the other films is delicately balanced though does provide us with a deficit in the expanse of the overall film. The impressive performance by real life boxer Antonio Tarver makes the action of the movie extraordinary and provides us with a quality in the opposition of Balboa which is unparalleled in other movies, even from Rocky V which featured a real life boxer performance which was quite good. This is a rich film with plenty to deal with and it will leave you with a kernel of wisdom, will get your motor going with its eliciting of high energy emotions and it will get you interested in the plot which never stops developing.
A testament to the greatness of Stallone from which you can say he is truly someone who has earned his place in film history and as a cultural icon, whatever you may feel about him otherwise.

PERFECT BLUE predicted our everyday lives over twenty years ago -- it takes place in a world where privacy is unknown, social media exists to manipulate its users, fantasy and reality are intertwined to the point that one is as terrifying as the other, and where people exhibiting signs of PTSD are just part of the background. The late Satoshi Kon's 1997 animated thriller makes its viewers as uncertain of what's real and what isn't as its victimized heroine, ending the story with a wink that dares us to believe there's any such thing as a "normal" to get back to.

This is more like a Brian De Palma movie than your typical anime, and the irony of its re-release by GKIDS (a distributor better known for the Studio Ghibli Collection) is as freaky as PERFECT BLUE itself: what with the nudity, film-within-a-film rape scenes, and death by icepick, this ain't no kids' movie.

Now that we've gotten used to super-slick computer animation, this hand-drawn film looks its age, but the story will drag you in -- and drag you under -- so quickly you'll barely notice.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review: I would give it 6 stars if I could
review_word:
The machine arrived all ready to go. I put in on the counter (fits fine, the footprint is well-thought-out by the manufacturer), wiped out the bowl and quickly washed (with a little soapy water) the blade, nut, cover, and spoon ... this took all of 5 minutes maybe. I had already researched my recipes, I need low-fat, lactose-free, calorie-restricted treats, and following the manufacturer's on-line pdf version of the manual I came up with this:

Two cups Fairlife Skim Milk (lactose free and low sugar) plus 3/4 cup organic Vermont maple syrup (purchased at a local discount store on the cheap). Poured one on top of the other in to a 4-cup measuring cup and put in the fridge so it wouldn't warm up in the kitchen (the milk and maple syrup were already in the fridge, of course) -- no mixing, no prep whatsoever, and turned on the machine's chiller for 15 minutes (set the timer to 45 minutes) as suggested by reviewers here and by the genius at icecreamscience<dot>com. After Alexa told me the 15 minutes were up, I dumped the contents of the measuring cup in to the bowl, turned on the churner, and told Alexa to alert me in 17 minutes and 30 seconds, again following icecreamscience.

When that period ended, I turned off the chiller for a few minutes as recommended by the manufacturer, then turned off the churner and served. We got FIVE nice portions of a smooth, creamy maple-flavored treat, plenty sweet and VERY tasty/refreshing. Everyone loved it.

I very carefully worked out the calories: 156 calories per serving. This is amazing. Yes, it's "ice milk", not ice cream, but it is wonderful. No additives, no fillers, ZERO work. One pour from each of two containers in to one measuring cup, that's it. And reasonably "natural", no?

Clean-up was a snap, following all the advice on Amazon. Use hot water, let the residue melt, protect the spindle opening, wipe up ... again, no more than 5 minutes, then hand-wash the lid, blade, nut, and spoon ... plus the measuring cup. Once again, just soapy water, super fast and easy. I plan to use a food-grade dairy-machine-oriented disinfectant (Amazon sells them in little packages and also in tablets) with a (glass) sprayer bottle maybe once a week.

In under an hour from the machine showing up at my door I was serving 4 people (and I had the 5th serving!) an amazing silky-smooth taste-great frozen treat with no lactose, virtually no fat, fully FODMAP-friendly, and as much control over the sugar as I could manage.

I am blown away. And should I need them, replacement covers, blades, etc. are available from the distributor in NJ. It doesn't get any better. I plan to move on to strawberry-based, pineapple-based, and coffee-based frozen treats, all with lower-calories in mind, now that I understand the basics. Lots of good advice on these ingredients in the manual.

Six stars.

The theatrical release of this movie would be on the list of what I would consider to be my “favorite” films. Being in the mood to watch it again, Prime or Netflix wasn’t offering it in their libraries (as of this writing, Prime is now showing the theatrical release. Yay!), so I jumped on Amazon to rent it. I discovered there was a directors cut. Wow, a chance to see one of my favorites, only better, because the director wasn’t being restricted by the stupid studio, right? Wrong! Way wrong! Watching both versions verifies two very import facets of filmmaking. 1) The film score is critically important. The score for the director’s cut is bland and in my opinion, detracts from the film. The theatrical release, which is decidedly noir, has a very supportive score, which punctuates the dark humor. 2) Studios know what sells. If you are a budding film critic or a full-time film student, you’ll love the director’s cut. However, everyone else will frickin’ hate it, compared to theatrical release. Why? Because the theatrical release is more ENTERTAINING, whereas the director’s cut is “dark and raw.” Guess what film critics? We ALL get a dose of reality every day and for many of us, it’s DARK and RAW. We don’t want to see a mirror of our troubled lives—we want to take a short break from it and be ENTERTAINED. Please, please, please watch the theatrical release of this movie. And hey, Amazon! Don’t mix the reviews of theatrical releases with other cuts of films. It’s misleading and inaccurate.

The first Rocky movie captured lightning in a bottle and they've been trying to recreate it since; to no avail. I feel bad for younger generations who will never be able to experience what it was like to see the first Rocky in the theater in 1976. The excitement that built during the fight scenes was palpable and had had a theater full of white people yelling and cheering. There was thunderous applause at the end of the movie. It was a stirring experience.

I see what this film is trying to do and be. I appreciate the message. But the fight scenes were too obviously fake (meaning I could tell the young guy was holding back, and it was obvious how slow Stallone was). And sadly, I spent a lot of the movie wondering what was going on with Stallone's eyebrows and hair. I never saw Rocky V, but to hear he was basically brain damaged in it, and to have it followed up with this with no explanation is...well, I can only shake my head. Thanks for the memories, but this just underlines the idea that you can't go home again.

review: A must see for all families with kids!
review_word:
This is truly an American Classic. If you wan't a great family story that's uplifting, musical and fun. This is it! Many families will probably end up watching this movie many times over so it's probably best to get a permanent copy.

Although not originally an American story it's one of Disney's 'great' films as there aren't really any these days.

The story is about a mystical/magical nanny who comes to visit a wealthy family in London. She can fly and do all kinds of magical things. Through the power of her goodness she changes the lives of the entire family and manages to turn awfully naughty kids into good little angels!

Came on perfect condition. The disk was not secured in place but that could be due to shipping and handling. I love this movie, if you are a Disney fan, this is a most own kind of a deal. The box was in good condition. Very happy with purchase.

We were overjoyed when the first time we showed her Mary Poppins she sat there enamored throughout the entire movie. She loves it so much, she has already asked to be Jane Banks for Halloween (5 months from now!). The movie is an absolute joy, and looks even better than I remember as a kid thanks to the high definition blu-ray image quality and sound.

An amazing added bonus is the digital copy that comes with the disc. With it, we were able to download the movie to our Amazon Fire for watching offline on long car rides. As a longer kids movie, it's such a great help to be able to keep our daughter entertained on the go.

review: A satisfying remaster that needed to happen.
review_word:
Riddle Box has always been a great album, but the production has always been sub par. Even 10 years ago when I didn't know much about music production or have a good ear, I noticed that the two albums before this sounded better.
Thankfully, it has finally been remastered and it sounds glorious. The bass and low tones are fuller, the samples are clearer, the vocals have been improved and it finally sounds closer to Great Milenko and less like The Terror Wheel.
Unfortunately, these sold out quick and now you have to pay a pretty penny. Originally priced at $30, I've seen some go for $80 and there is currently one listed for $750!
If you have the money or find a reasonably priced version, get it. It'll be worth every penny. It also includes a bonus disc of outtakes and a booklet with stories about each song.

As a Greek Mythology fan, I was appalled by the distortions (like Hera being Hercules’s mother - hello! Not!!! Talk about sanitizing in some family values, which is ironic given how hideously they twisted Hera’s *actual* mythological son - Hades). But even if you don’t care about that, you might care about the nonstop eye-averting ugliness happening on the screen throughout the movie. Really, really bad on all meaningful levels.

review: I thought Elizabeth Taylor was supposed to be a GOOD actor!
review_word: My son is taking a Shakespeare course, and we've been watching a number of movies from Shakespeare plays. Neither of us had seen a production of Taming of the Shrew. I picked this film because of the famous actors and famous director. Both my son and I hated this production! Elizabeth Taylor's Katharina was more like a violently insane person. Richard Burton's Petruchio was a hedonistic, sexist ass (yes, I realize that's just part of how Shakespeare wrote the character) with completely unrealistic reactions to Katharina's lunacy and violence. I mean, this is supposed to be one of Shakespeare's comedies. But I would say this production was tragic. And, if this was a fair representation of Elizabeth Taylor's and Richard Burton's acting chops, then I have absolutely no idea why they were such lauded and sought after actors in their time. Ugh. We even liked "10 Things I Hate About You" better than this movie, and that was NOT much of a movie.

Been listening to Styx since HS, and they have pretty much been one of my favorite bands since. I own most their stuff, and pretty much love it all. Of course, their best stuff is from Equinox to Paradise Theater, but those were a unique times in life too, with growing up and all. I listened to their music with my friends, but even more while I was reading scifi novels. They are basically part of the landscape of all the books I read. So the memories of Styx, and other bands back then, are tied to me more than most music I picked up over the years. They really do have a unique spot in my life.

With all that said, Brave New World pretty much fits in with my idea of what Styx is. Just need to give it a go and a chance. I had to be reeled in a bit, and listen to it some, which is pretty normal for most music I like, but once I did, it definitely felt, and sounded like a Styx album. And sadly, the last one from the line up we all know so well. I look at it as a parting gift from them, and its not a bad send off at all. So no, I can't put it up there with my top era, but I can definitely add it to my collection and enjoy it on it's own. I think the whole album is pretty good, however, i have to say I could have done without 'High Crimes & Misdemeanors'. That song should be stricken from the record.

review: The peak of 80s heavy metal sound
review_word: A good portion of heavy metal fans will criticize this album for sounding "too commercial," but I personally love the sound and aesthetic of this album. Yes, this album is pretty much the 1980s summarized in 40 minutes, and there is a certain cheesiness to it, but if you love 80s metal, I think this is the peak of that era. There is no shortage of chorus effects and synthesizers here. At the same time, Turbo still remains distinctly Judas Priest. Yes they succumbed to the trends somewhat, but they were pretty faithful to the heavy metal genre nonetheless. I think this album is a lot of fun, sounds decent, and includes a couple of nice bonus tracks. I think if you're a lover of both 1980s culture and heavy metal music, you should have no problem enjoying this.

You know you've entered a powerful world when you suddenly realize you've forgotten that what you're watching is nothing but ink and paint. But, oh my god, what this master of animation does with mere ink and paint is absolutely breathtaking. At first, you believe you're watching just some silly, brainless, pop-culture fluff. And, yes, it is showing you what that culture is like. But almost at the same moment, you become aware of a deep, very dark and twisted level of human depravity and pain.

The strangest part of this film is that the director/writer makes you feel sympathy with the worst of the characters he draws for you. Not at first, of course. At first, you are thoroughly repulsed and sickened by these people. But slowly, as you watch what they do and how and why they think as they do, you cannot help but feel a twinge of compassion. They are just as much victims of an ugly, twisted system as those who are openly exploited.

I was under the mistaken belief that this turned out to be the last film made by Satoshi Kon, the creator who made Millennium Actress and Tokyo Godfathers, besides other impressive films. In fact, Millennium Actress, from 2019(?), was, I believe, his last film. These all are outstanding works of art, not just "cartoons". You get the feeling with his work that had he the funds, he would certainly have made live-action versions of his stories. But, budgets being what they are, he had to settle for anime. Still, his work is just as masterful and important as anything coming out of Ghibli. It's just a shame that this man had to die so young. I suspect we've been robbed of some truly unique and powerful films. Oh, well. That's life -- such as it is.

Again, I must emphasize that this film is rather deceptively simple. By the time you've gotten half-way through the story, you are absolutely hooked. Several times, I was rather surprised to realize that my mouth was open in shock at what I was seeing. The power of the sound and images he created is simply overwhelming. You quickly forget that you're watching a film; you are pulled, intellectually, emotionally, totally, into the story this man is telling. And even though the scenes you witness seem to be exploitative, the truth is that he is actually showing you exactly how the entertainment industry exploits the people it sucks into its web.

I'm certain he intended this to be an indictment of the Japanese entertainment industry. But we all know that the world-wide entertainment industry operates along the very same lines. In fact, truth be known, it is far, far worse than any of us suspect. Only recently have some brave individuals been able to come out publicly and reveal just how perverse this industry truly is. Yes, we have whistle-blowers in every industry. But the entertainment industry operates at a truly depraved level of exploitation only recently being revealed. item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker Follow up review
review_word:
I purchased this machine about 4 weeks ago. My previous ice cream machine was one I purchased from Sur le Table. It appeared to have been a generic machine. Don't recall the manufacturer. It worked ok and stimulated my interest in making frozen deserts.

One of my concerns regarding the Lello 4080 was cleaning the bowl since the stainless steel bowl is not removable. Apparently this enhances the freezing of it's contents. Actually it's not too bad to clean. Just wipe it out a few times and you are done. I have some concern about getting liguid down into the mechanism through the spindle so I leave the paddle on until the last. It's a bit harder to clean but seems safer to me.

I have made 4 batches of ice cream and it works beautifully. The ice crystals must be smaller because the product is very smoothe . The maximum amount of custard is 900 ml. I don't know what the final volume is but I think it may be a little less than 1 1/2 quart.

Surprised there is no temperature readout on the thing but I guess it is not to know the temperature but rather go by what the ice cream looks like.

So far I am 100% pleased with the Lello 4080. I suggest adding about 3 tablespoons of vodka or liqueur to the recipe to keep the ice cream from hardening when you place it in the freezer. There is a difference! I am not sure what makes this machine so good. Maybe it's the rotation speed or the cooling element or possibly the paddle.

I would recommend it. Expensive but hopefully you will not need more than 1! I did get the Asurian warranty offered on Amazon. The price on Amazon is good. An Italian supplier asked $799. on Ebay and would not budge.

Enjoy our ice cream!

Follow-up
I have been using this machine for over a year with good results. After reading other reviews I guess you either get a good one or a bad one. Fortunately for me I received one that works perfectly. I still suggest care in cleaning so that contents don't get into the works through the spindle. A small balloon over the spindle might help! Another suggestion is that you completely clean out the contents or let it melt completely before starting another batch. I had some extra from a previous batch and thought I could just dump it in. The machine made some terrible noises from the gear box when it encountered the frozen part at the bottom. I thought I had killed it but is still working fine. Amazon sells Asurion warranty which I purchased. I had a warranty issue with a dishwasher and Asurion was very difficult to work with. Finally got it deemed unrepairable and received a refund but was without a dishwasher for 2 months. Up to you! Adding some Vodka or flavored liquor will help keep the ice cream soft in the freezer. Maximum of 3T vodka per quart. This machine works fast and makes fine ice cream. If you are serious about ice cream I think this machine is for you. Hope you get one of the good ones. See other reviewers problems.

item: Officemate Heavy Duty Weighted 2-in-1 Tape Dispenser, Recycled,Black (96660)
review_word:
It seems like a full five-star review is too good to be true, but not with this product! It's 100% true. My dad and I opened an eBay store recently and make multiple trips to the post office with about 5-20 packages daily; needless to say we go through a lot of packing tape. My dad uses the 3m tape dispensers and he does okay with them after using them for over 10 years in his retail experience but NOT me. Those things hate me! The tape always comes out sideways on the roll causing it to tangle and twist when I really need it not too! Now shipping labels are my primary focus and I can very easily pullout even long pieces of packing tape and they come out perfect and cut very easily! Using the small tape dispenser has been a breeze as well; having them side by side has completely changed the shipping game!

I was hesitant because in some of the reviews it showed the circular rings that hold the tape in place popped out, but once locked in place those puppies don't come out! They hold very sturdy and allow for easy pulling and tearing. The base of the dispenser is very heavy and sturdy, I believe it weighs almost 6 lbs. total. It also includes rubber feet in each corner plus a rubber pad on the bottom which prevents any sliding while taping.

If I could order 50 more of these I would!! So worth it for the price point! You'll also save more $$ by using less tape because it's much easier to take out the amount of tape needed for each package!

Sorry for the long review, I just love giving info. :-)

review_word: New CD, never open

review: It is Faux Twenty and a Splendid Time is Guaranteed for All
review_word:
This is the best early CB&tMB. The music is better now than when it was first recorded and released. How is that possible?

The band was prime then and very advanced considering their contemporaries. This group acted upon their vision and talents to pursue their vision. Many of their contemporaries were, in essence, reacting to the time, the scene, and the perceptions and prejudices of 1960s society. This makes the Captain and this version of the Magic Band nearly timeless, which in turn makes them still relevant.

The music is both ancient (e.g., blues-based) and forward-looking, at the same time. They were ahead of their time by being based in the past and the future at the same time. Soon, The Captain and the Magic would morph and mutate into the Piscean-faced Verisimilitude. They would literally take a giant step outside their collective mind.

This particular version of the endlessly fascinating album (now on CD) is an incredibly-priced bargain. The original tracks are rendered in pristine 'Back to Mono'. Just as John Lennon advocated. Ry Cooder sounds magnificent. Drumbo is masterful. The bass guitar figures are truly psychedelic, rather than the usual (for this time period) stereotypical hippie-trippy claptrap. The Cap'n writes, sings, growls and plays various non-rock instruments in his distinct and unique style, which moves his vision ever forward. Not bad for over fifty years ago.

The extra tracks are truly a bonus grab bag of titles gleaned from the Mirror-Man sessions, etc. These items are in stereo and vary from a B-side release to standard length demos and unused takes. Included on this disc are two hallucinogenic titles sporting mini-opus recording lengths. Wow!

If you have even a passing fancy in a midnite dream for this music, these musicians, or the time period, then swallow a full dose of this concoction. After all, It IS 'Safe as Milk'.

Anaconda (before being beloved for the ball of crap that it is) was promoted as this amazing movie with a glowing cast and budget. It's the movie that paid five million dollars to JLo. At that time it was unheard for a Latina to make that kind of money and to start in a huge horror/action movie. It was like jungle Alien...not. King Cobra was a modest straight to video flick with no pretensions. It doesn't take itself seriously. It looks bad because its cheap. It's poorly written because it was developed fast. Nonetheless, it's a super fun movie that contains stereotypical cholos, stereotypical bad 90's music, stereotypical rednecks, impossibly ridiculous science, a mad scientist, cheese drama, cheese romance, and Eric Estrada failing at being a gay stereotype. On top of that a top performance from a vicious giant snake. You can see the contempt it was for humanity on its penetrating gaze! review: Beastie Boys changed my life with this cd
review_word: I absolutely love this cd and it changed my life! it was one of the 2 first cds I bought when I got my first cd player. and this was back when cd players first came out. they were clunky things that you plugged into your existing stereo. they were well over a $100. Anime reviewers always bring up Satoshi Kon's work when talking about their favorite movies. I finally had the chance to watch one of his works, and boy am I glad I did.

Mima is a pop idol who has decided to shift careers into being an actress. Starting out on a seedy tv drama, she is pushed to do some sketchy scenes to advance her career. Her stress is compounded by a website she finds online that seems to be run by a stalker. Over time, the stress of both of these things causes her to lose her grip on who she is and what is actually going on in her life. If you've ever watched Black Swan, it's quite similar to that.

The animation direction is stunningly good in this movie. Despite the dated art style, the use of cuts brings out the insanity in what Mina is going through, and the body language given to every character is nearly indistinguishable from live action. This movie is the perfect way to spend an afternoon

item: I'm Glad You're Here With Me Tonight
review_word: Decades ago, I lived with my oldest brother when I first listened to this amazing album. I can't count the number of times we both air-guitared our way through Lament in D Minor/Sabre Dance on hot August nights. It is an inspired, joyful piece of music. Since that time, my brother left us, and I eventually threw out all of my record albums when I thought that albums would never be around again. Now records have made a comeback. So, I bought a really good turntable. I knew I had to buy this album again to relive those moments in the basement of my brother's house, because only music has that way of playing back scenes of a life. Music really is the soundtrack to our lives. The music of this album, and that song in particular, are as powerful today as they ever were. I bought the album for the music and the moments they evoke. And I can play back those moments whenever I want, when the needle lands with such grace and precision on the record grooves. Thank you, Neil Diamond.

review: Great Retelling of a Classic Tale
review_word:
Disney's "Hercules" is an upbeat rendition of the classic myth. It tells the simple story of an immortal being trying to find the place where he belongs. Sterling performances by Danny DeVito who plays Hercules' satyr trainer Philoctetes (Phil) and Susan Egan as Megara (Meg) his wise-talking love interest. James Woods voices the god Hades, the villain of the piece who comes across like a ruthless executive, making shady deals with everyone and hoping no one sees the fine print. The songs are top notch, sung by the muses who tell the story and interact with the characters. Parents might want to familiarize their kids with the original myth so they can understand the film as it is full of classical references which will go over the head of the average child (the muses aren't going to explain everything).
The film has been panned by religious types who take offense at everything. Incredibly, it has also been panned by the Greek Government who think we Yankees have no right tampering with their cultural past--even though they no longer worship that cultural past. These two negative attitudes simply prove that conservatism is the root of all anal and cause this reviewer to quote a line from the film: "Lighten up, dude!"
If you don't like this film, your life is indeed a Greek tragedy.

This is a reissue of the album's release, all original pressing released literally 20 years ago, with some limited/collector's editions with later demands. If you're new to radiohead, I'd suggest giving this a listen, or OK Computer.

Trivia: Kid A's promotional campaign introduced the infamous "bear" logo. This logo is still present today for modern Radiohead marketing and association for the bands merchandise.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review: You get what you pay for!
review_word:
yes it hurt to pay the price, but now it is done, i have no regrets, actually the whole family loves it.

One thing i never found info on that i figured out & works for me is this:
I premix my basic ice cream recipe into a quart sized jar, I use the quart size because as it freezes it increases its volume, and in the end, it fills my 1.5 quart containers i bought. I mix sugar, (cocoa powder if needed) half and half, 30% whipping cream and vanilla bean paste or just plain vanilla extract. I shake it up to mix and then its ready. i usually turn on the machine until the bowl is cold to the touch. maybe 5 - 10 minutes with the compressor running I then pour in the 1 quart jar of mix, turn on the mixing bar and let it rock...
since my cream and half and half live in the fridge they are already chilled so it doesn't take long to see it thicken. any extra ingredients like, coffee( I prefer fresh ground, not actual coffee), nuts or jam, or other last minute additions go in as it thickens.... and when it is stiffened up a bit it is basically soft serve at this point, ready for a party to use immediately, or, as I prefer put it in a good container and set into the freezer and let it set up! it can be made ahead of time, but it is fun to make while everyone is enjoying the main food course.
as for removing the ice cream, i bought a set of silicone spatulas and I like the broad kind that has a scoop shape to it, and remove as much as i can then remove the mixer bar, then finish the bowl as best you can.

To clean I usually sprinkle a little water to soften the residual ice cream frozen to the walls, then sop it up with paper towels and it usually comes clean. at his point, if i am making multiple batches, I re-engage the cooler and repeat the procedure.
although it is a substantial sized device we managed to tuck it into a corner and hardly know its there, but never is it forgotten, it is quick and easy to pull out and fire up and pull a single batch or multiple batches. and it opens up a whole world to explore, my journey has just begun.

its a great machine if you can budget it in you wont regret it, unless you are struggling with your weight... good luck on that. LOL

Blueberry cheesecake
Blueberry
rocky road
coffee
peanut butter
pistachio
toasted almond with real maple syrup
I am planning:
irish cream
burbon
rum (goslings black seal) and ginger beer with lime.

and the list goes on...

Under appreciated gem here with turbo. I love this album. It's filled with great songs if you just accept it's not going to sound like painkiller or stained class. It is what is. Turbo lover is the hardest driving song on here. The buildup to the chorus is fantastic with the guitar creeping in as the chorus approaches. Robs vocal is fantastic on that song and the entire record, considering this was his first record and tour sober, and it shows. Out in the cold is the groups best ballad IMO. The synth mixed with the heavy guitar is awesome. It sounds great on vinyl with some good mid range. Hot for love is great, the bit right before the chorus gets me every time. Obviously locked in is an awesome tune. Love that song. The synth at the beginning and the chorus is great with that one. Then there's reckless. That song stands out in it's own realm. Possibly the one song from this album that could have fit in proudly on any of their heavier more accepted albums. It contains possibly the heaviest, crunchiest, nastiest riff that they ever came up with throughout their entire discography. It sits within my top 5 favorite riffs of all time. The mastering on this album is great and is actually softer and less treble focused than the 30th anniversary release, which is good. The sleeve came in great condition along with the record as well.

This album was a revelation when it came out in 1986 because it was a highly artistic, professionally produced CCM album. It's different today—guys like Sufjan Stevens and the band Son Lux can be Christian and write artistic music that reflects their faith in a mainstream market. But back then, if it didn’t sound like adult contemporary, it wasn’t played on Christian radio stations. “The Big Picture” is still among what I consider the best CCM albums ever made during that period in the sense of purely artistic merit—and that’s a pretty short list: Mark Heard’s masterpiece, “The Dry Bones Dance” is one. Dylan’s “Slow Train Coming.” Phil Keaggy’s “Town to Town,” Chagall Guevera’s self-titled album, The 77s “Sticks and Stones.” There are others, but you get the idea. MWS has always been "McCartney-esque" in his ability to write incredibly catchy, hooky music, but he's not a lyricist. "The Big Picture" was the first time Smith teamed up with lyricist Wayne Kirkpatrick, and it was a brilliant pairing. He also got John Potoker to produce the album--who worked with Genesis, Madonna, Scritti Politti, etc. Suddenly, there was a Christian album that SOUNDED like the stuff on rock stations rather than adult contemporary music. Not only that, but the lyrics were full of metaphors--they were actually poetic! Now, 34 years later, I'm 56 years old, I still really love most of the songs on this album--Lamu, Wired for Sound, Rocketown, Voices, Goin' Thru the Motions, You're Alright--I'm still impressed with the lyrics and music. The music and production is similar to Genesis in the 80s--Abacab & Invisible Touch—synths, drum machines and bright distorted Fender guitars. My only complaint is that "The Big Picture" would really benefit from a remaster. But as I understand it, this was Smith’s least successful album, (and evidently the companies that own CCM masters from the 70s & 80s consider it such ephemera they won’t even release most of it as mp3s). So there’s not much hope of a remaster. His follow-up, "I 2 Eye" was much more CCM mainstream. By the time he released "Go West Young Man," he and Kirkpatrick had shifted to the David Foster/Chicago power ballad sound, and he had a big mainstream hit with "Place in this World" (which sounds like it could've been in a Disney's "Aladdin"). In my opinion, Smith never took the risks he took on "The Big Picture" ever again. He still made great music CCM--the guy's a genius--but as far as genuine artistry goes, this is his White Album.

review: (Vinyl review) Bad pressing. Do not buy until Craft Recordings figures this out.
review_word:
I love this album and when I saw Craft Recordings released it on vinyl I got very excited. I own several other Craft Recordings releases (Cheating at Solitaire by Mike Ness and Violent Femmes self titled) and they all sound fantastic. I, Jonathan however, has some serious issues. I have now purchased and returned this record 3 times from Amazon and other vendors because on the first track (Parties in the U.S.A.) there is a very audible crackling that occurs about halfway through the song. The crackling is mostly present on the peaks of Jonathan's vocals and continues intermittently throughout the rest of side 1. These artifacts occur in the exact same spots on all three records I purchased and is absent when comparing it to any of the digital versions. I Spincleaned all of them and it made little to no difference. Plus, all 3 records have a ton of vinyl shavings peeling off the razor-sharp unfinished edges. Such a shame because the rest of the record sounds great and is dead quiet with no warps etc. Hopefully Craft Recordings figures this out but until then I'm keeping my money. Another casualty of the modern vinyl quality fade.

Update: Per Discogs this record was pressed by Rainbow Records. No wonder.

review: 5-Star Movie, but the "Director's Definitive Edition" Brings It Down
review_word:
Heat is one of the greatest movies of all time, bringing in two legendary actors playing characters who are two sides of the same coin - one a professional who takes down high-level scores and the other a homicide detective whose life is defined by the hunt for those types of criminals, but both suffering flaws and breakdowns due to their personal codes and the paths they've chosen. The rest of the cast is excellent, and the way the story plays out, with ebbs and flows and highs and lows, quiet contemplative scenes and ear-shattering gunfights, it just mesmerizes you.*

I can only give 4-stars for the newer blu-ray release though, because personally I found it to be a bit of a let down. Much like other redone releases, the clarity and sharpness are excellent, and there are some nice new features like a cast/crew interview by Christopher Nolan (no inclusion of the original tv movie "LA Takedown" though, which would have been nice). The problem is that Mann, like others, has re-color timed the movie, so a lot of it has a light blue hue and just looks weird. This is something that plagues a lot of releases (Terminator 2, Batman, Blade Runner, etc) and takes away from the experience. I'm also annoyed at the removal of the line "viscous, aren't I?", as now you just see Hank Azaria's face frozen for a few seconds and again, it feels out of place.

*Slight detractions in the cast include Diane Venora as Hanna's ex wife (pretentious to a fault) and Kevin Gage as Waingro, who just doesn't fit with any of Neil's crew or the rest of the characters.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review_word:
This machine is a beast among kitchen appliances. All stainless outside, a stainless metal churning blade (dasher), and it weighs close to 40 pounds. It is built to last, and is truly a mini-industrial appliance, as well as being beautiful kitchen art (it IS Italian!), with every external part clad in shiny metal - the only plastics to be seen are the clear lid, legs, timer dial and the two function buttons (and the provided scoop). It also does what it was made to do, flawlessly - make ice cream. And not just "ice cream" - gelato, soft-serve, hard cream, frozen yogurt, sorbet - every type of frozen confection. And it does it in about 15 to 20 minutes, average.

Ice cream is, basically, a pretty simple confection - water/milk/cream, sugar, and other "stuff." Mixed together and frozen. The "mix together" and "freezing" parts are where it gets complicated. The mixing and freezing make all the difference in the mouth feel, texture, workability (scooping, plopping on your ice cream cone, plate or cup), consistency, and overall perceived "quality" of the ice cream. No one likes ice cream with big chunks of ice in it, or hard in one spot, soft in another, or a titanium brick when you try to scoop it. This machine makes perfectly consistent ice cream, batch after batch, ready to serve out of the machine, or to put in your freezer. It does this by rapid churning and rapid cooling, making the smallest crystals perfectly blended, resulting in an even, smooth blend of ingredients, chilled to the perfect stage of completion.

As far as the machine itself, in this age of Bluetooth and WiFi connectivity, digital readouts, iPhone and Android apps, it's an absolute evolutionary throwback. It has three controls - a twist dial 'click' timer (which doesn't go backwards - when you set it for 30 minutes, it will click down to 30 minutes until it stops), and two function buttons - one to turn on the churning blade and one to turn on the compressor (it's a compressor machine that chills internally - no freezing extra containers, no ice, no rock salt). That's it. The function of the timer is to power the buttons - when the timer is running, the buttons work. When the timer is off, pressing the buttons does nothing. The timer is actually probably redundant (there is no alarm), except as a reminder, or to make sure the machine is off when it stops, because you will be monitoring the final stages of your mix - ice cream mixes and freezes, as you probably know, at it's own pace - it's done when it's done, depending on a hundred variables, even with the same mix. You'll actually hear a change in the motor as the ice cream hardens, and the blades will move slower - in fact on this machine, when the ice cream is completely set, the blades will stop - time to take it out. For those who are particular about their ice cream and to reduce stress on the motor, most mixes are best removed when the mix reaches an optimum temp: 21F-23F (the "draw" temperature), which can be measured with a cheap IR thermometer. And I've never had a batch take more than 30 minutes, although I suppose there might be exotic ingredients that might take longer - but I can't imagine any mix taking the full 60 minute maximum on the timer. Adding ingredients at any time is as simple as lifting the plastic mixing cavity cover and dropping them in.

Cleanup is actually a breeze, in spite of the non-removable mixing cavity - it's all stainless. Just scoop out the ice cream, remove the blade by lifting out after unscrewing the retaining nut (you do need to cover the exposed blade shaft to prevent liquid getting inside - I did it with a simple rubber spacer), and remove the remaining ice cream. You then just wipe out the bowl with soapy water after it warms up slightly, rinse with a damp towel and dry. Finished. You learn not to be messy (with any ice cream machine), and minimize drips on counter or self.

The weak point of the machine is the 1 year warranty - and the cost. Well over $700, a 1 year warranty is nervous-making, although I don't know how many have had to use it - I consequently highly recommend Amazon's extended warranty, and I don't usually purchase add-on warranties. You may never need it (and likely won't - it's really an industrial quality build), but nice to have on such an expensive machine. The cost is worth it, to me, because I bought the machine to do one thing - make ice cream. And it does this superbly. Highly recommended.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review: Worth Every Penny For Frequent User
review_word:
Did a lot of research and read a lot of product reviews in my quest for an authentic Italian Gelato machine. I've had the old Cuisinart home ice cream machine in the past, where you freeze the bowl first, and I didn't want to deal with having to freeze the bowl again, I wanted a self-contained refrigerated unit, of which there are really only 3 of that I considered (this one, the Breville and the Cuisinart). There are cheap Chinese knock-offs that Amazon is pushing of course, just like every other product, and I refuse to buy any of that garbage. So despite the outrageous price I decided to give this one a shot primarily based upon the Italian manufacturing (not China) since I've had great luck with other Italian appliances. As noted in many other reviews, this unit is robust, heavy and powerful.

To clarify on a couple of the most common "complaints" from other reviews I read - here's my perspective:

1) CLAIM: It's heavy, so you need to find a place to park this an never move it. Hogwash! It weighs 38 lbs. not 138 lbs. I have it stored in my pantry and when I want to use it I grab it and set it on my kitchen counter right next to the sink, when I'm done I put it back in the pantry. Perhaps if you're not capable of carrying 38 lbs. a few feet then it would be an issue (elderly, weak body type, etc.) but I'd say for most people it's not going to be an issue. My wife can carry it no problem.

2) CLAIM: It doesn't have a removable bowl so it's hard to clean. Hogwash! This is probably the easiest to clean appliance I own. The entire thing is stainless steel and the bowl and top are highly polished stainless steel, it doesn't get any easier to clean than that. Here's what I do to clean it. Make gelato. Scoop gelato out with a silicone spatula, leaving very little in the bowl. Leave the unit turned off and just sit for 10 minutes to let the bowl unfreeze. Take a paper towel and wipe out what's left. Wet another paper towel and wipe the bowl out. Take a dry paper towel and do a final wipe of the bowl. It literally takes 30 seconds to clean this and it looks brand new every time. Just don't try to clean it immediately when the bowl is still frozen, let it melt and then it's a piece of cake.

NOTE: You DO need to be careful when removing the blade to not get the threads of the bolt that holds the blade on full of gelato since it would be difficult to fully clean that off.

I don't have a long-term reliability perspective since I've only had it a short time, but I've made 10 batches of gelato in it now, and it's perfect every time. I pre-cool the unit for 10 minutes by turning on the compressor before making the gelato. I always use fully chilled base in the fridge for at least several hours. Using it in that manner, my churning time is 15 minutes every time, and it comes out very smooth and perfect. I set the timer for 20 minutes, and when it approaches 15 minutes in I just listen to the churning, as soon as I start to hear the motor start to work a little harder I know it's done and I stop there.

THE ONLY annoying thing about this unit is the old-fashioned ticking countdown timer can't be reset to 0 manually, once you turn it on you have to just let it count down, so even if you shut the unit off early before the timer is done it just sits there ticking and counting down until the time is up and then "ding" it lets you know the timer is done. It's just and old-fashioned design, but at the same time it will probably last forever since it's a very basic analog timer and not some fancy digital timer that relies on a computer chip.

So I think the bottom line is if you want to make gelato frequently, and you don't mind spending a few extra bucks on a premium appliance that you'll plan to own for decades, this is worth it. If you start doing the "I can make the same quality gelato in a unit that costs less....." comparison, then this isn't for you. Maybe you can or maybe you can't make the same quality gelato in the Cuisinart or Breville or the junky Amazon chinabdrand one, but you can FOR SURE make the highest quality gelato in this one and you'll enjoy owning something this nice (and Italian).

I bought the first KANSAS album in 1974, and saw them on tour at Grove City University just prior to the release of this, their second album. I have never missed buying a new KANSAS release on release day since 1974! Like many people, in the 80s when it looked like vinyl was obsolete, I sold many of the albums I had (a couple thousand!) including my KANSAS collection up to and including POWER, the last of the vinyl for many years. I of course, replaced all of the albums with CDS, and just in the past couple of years have been buying vinyl again because I like the overall sound quality much better than CDS, and especially MP3 versions. I personally like the dynamic range of vinyl much better. The bass sounds better to me, and the warmth of the vinyl is soothing and not harsh to my ears AND body. Dropping the needle on these FRIDAY releases is a better experience than it was in the 70s and 80s when I first got this music. SONG FOR AMERICA has some amazing music! The title track, of course, but the majestic LAMPLIGHT SYMPHONY always dug deep into my soul. Passionate, powerful and graceful. Steve Walsh sang his heart out, and Robby Steinhardt's violin take this song to places unimaginable. The original 6 members of the band with the ever thoughtful and searching writing of Kerry Livgren will never be matched by any other group of musicians. At the time Kerry was soul searching and his writing moved many young people like myself to look deeper. (Sadly, he took a turn into Contemporary Christian Music and never found a combination of musicians to come close to the presentation of his ideas like these guys. This album also features the epic INCOMUDRO - HYMN TO THE ATMAN, a 12 minute progressive rock journey that will rock your very soul! Every song on this release is excellent, but I have to mention the incredible DOWN THE ROAD, a rockin' song that features the late singer/violinist co - front man, Robby Steinhardt. This was always a show stopper in concert. So, anyone buying the vinyl will probably know all of this information, but I HIGHLY recommend ANY vinyl products from FRIDAY MUSIC. The 180gm vinyl sounds incredible! This album EVEN COMES AS A GATEFOLD, which it had never been on it's original release! You just can't go wrong with the FRIDAY LABEL when they have their hands on a classic release like this!!

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review: Quiet, simple to use, works just fine
review_word:
a. takes about 20 minutes. to freeze up a quart of ice cream.
b. it is nice and quiet running... not like a hand crank, or motorized ICE & SALT unit.
c. Tried 2 different mixes - both were creamy & smooth.

For real SUCCESS: let the dry mix & milk/water mixture sit in the fridge for 2 hours after mixing - not to prechill, but to allow enough time for the mixture to really combine. there is NO short cut, no, a blender does not speed it up, just mix it up, stick it in the fridge, maybe mix it again after an hour, but, in 2hrs of "chillin' in da fridge", it's ready to go - super creamy & smooth!

For FAILURE: Mix it up, don't taste test (daughter forgot to add SUGAR - ugh!), and don't let it sit for 2hrs in the fridge to fully combine. What you'll get is cream separation (yellow butter streaks & clumps), sugar lumps (even if you use a blender to really mix it - nope, we did that too).

We went with THIS unit, because the paddle was METAL. I had worked on these big units before - replaced plenty of broken parts for various reasons (unit set too cold, usually). It cost more, but we expect it to last longer too.

1.5qts sounds small - BUT, it's done in 20 minutes. Guess what! A 2 quart machine... takes 30 minutes!
The bowl doesn't come out - yeah, you WIPE it out, wash off the paddle, and it's clean.

Downside: It takes up counter space, like every other appliance, where the heck do you STORE these kinds of things that probably get used on weekends...?
----- updated ----

We ordered the Whynter ICM-201SB, and the another unit about 2x the price.
the Whynter ICM-201SB will freeze till it gets a little stiff, like milkshake consistency, and the motor peters out... a bit on the slushy or soft for a cone. OK, so we put it into the freezer - and the ice cream became a ICE-BRICK.

If the freezer is working correctly, it will add AIR into the ice cream as it freezes, giving you in volume more, with the air whipped into it. That's what makes it scoopable when it's really frozen hard. This machine does not do that, because it bogs down. After freezing, you'll have to let the ice cream "warm up" if you'd like to scoop it.

We make Vanilla, Chocolate, Lime-Vanilla flavors, from 3 different companies, between the Whynter ICM-201SB and the Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker. Both are brand new, one was ordered by accident.

Both machines got the exact same mix, chilled for 2 hrs before being put into the machines.

Lello 4080 Musso Lussino - ice cream increased in volume, as expected, was very stiff, and after being put into the freezer, was easily scoopable, able to stuff into a cone, stack 2-4 scoops high, as expected. the machine was cleaned with a warm rag, the parts are all metal, probably last a long time. machine is quiet. Bottom line: It does exactly what we expected, FREEZES ice cream mix properly, not leaving us with slush.

Whynter ICM-201SB - ice cream did not increase in volume, was quite soft when scooped out, and froze into a rock hard brick, which we chiseled apart to get it out of the container. right out of the machine, It was too soft to put into a cone without running all over. the machine was easy to clean, remove the bowl and wash it out, along with the paddle/stirrer. machine is quiet. If you want milkshakes - this is your machine, we were not impressed.

First, for many years I was put off from Radiohead by "OK Computer." It was only five or six years ago that I began listening to some of their more recent releases, beginning with "The King of Limbs," which I consider their second masterpiece. I also love the remixes of that album on "TKOL RMS 1234567." Nearly as good is "Moon Shaped Pool." Radiohead's fifth album, "Amnesiac," was recorded at the same time as the music on "Kid A," but in the end released separately a year later. I think it was a good choice, since the best of those tracks are on "Kid A," which I consider their first masterpiece. The packaging alone is a masterwork of numerous fold-out pages and translucent overlays. It took a few minutes to find the actual recording and track information.

Apparently, following "OK Computer" Yorke was burned out and looking for a new direction. He was influenced by a few ambient/electronic musicians and groups of the time, which led to the completely new sound of the tracks on this record—sounds, especially rhythms, that form the roots of Radiohead's music ever since, as well as that of Yorke's Atoms for Peace project. "Kid A" is probably the most important recording by Radiohead.

item: iLight Mini Smartphone 11 Pro The World's Smallest 11 Pro Android Mobile Phone, Super Small Micro 2.5" Touch Screen Global Unlocked Great for Kids 1GB RAM / 8GB ROM Tiny iPhone XI Pro Look Alike
review: You know why you're buying this
review_word:
The reason you're buying this is most likely because it's a tiny gimmick of a phone. Of course. I dare say, it's better than the "haha" I had hoped it would give me, and gave me the "please be more than useable" I really wanted.

The TL;DR is IT WORKS. ITS FUN. ITS TINY. ITS AMAZING. BUY THIS PHONE, THE PRICE IS WORTH IT. Seriously. I'm so extremely elated to own a tiny phone like this that can do most everything I expected from it.

To start, the screen. It's tiny, yes, but it's also looks pretty good. Peel off the manufacturer's fuzzy screen protector, and you have a serviceable screen. At that size, you need a high enough resolution that gives you clarity, and this phone delivers. Also, the text all seem to be manipulated by a custom android OS made to give legibility and formatting to work on the small screen. Chrome and other apps were all sized and formatted in a way that everything was easy to read, no need to zoom.

You might think typing is difficult on the screen, but my secret weapon for you is Gboard. Download the keyboard from the Play store, and turn on Glide. Boom, you can now swipe/Swype/glide with ease. I typed my typical book-long messages to my viewers in Discord with ease. Hangouts? No issues. Side note: there is a custom keyboard in it, it might have glide/Swype, but I didn't use it. Gboard is my jam, so I went with that.

I downloaded quite a few apps for this phone, and some intensive games. They all ran acceptably, but a few stuttered. Honestly, if you want to game hardcore, you're looking at the wrong phone. Emulating with a Bluetooth controller, though? Chefs kiss, babay, it handles the classics of the 16 bit era quite well. Definitely a nice teeny pocket handheld. And, hey, Alto's Adventure ran beautifully.

Quick tip: use Nova Launcher and give it a more traditional Android look, it'll make the phone feel more complete. It runs perfectly with a custom launcher.

The typical features of a phone were all FINE on this. Great volume, strong vibrate, the Bluetooth worked wonderfully to make this an MP3 player, and so on. The cameras on the front and back are pretty low quality in low light, but they snapped acceptable pics. You'll be wanting a different device for higher quality photos, come on. Battery life is great. Full charge in an hour, idled on for three days without dying. I left it sitting at 75 percent, from me playing on it for about 45 minutes. It might not be an all day phone using it nonstop, but the faster charge is nice.

Phone calls were great. If you don't want to hold a tiny phone, use Bluetooth. I used it, with zero issue, perfect call quality. Any bad areas in town were still bad areas with this phone, but that's to be expected.

Oh, also, it came with all the goodies. A screen protector. Charging cable. Sim card slot puller. AND A CUTE LITTLE CASE.

I use a Note 20 Ultra as my daily phone. I used this for 5 days straight, and will keep carrying it around, along with that behemoth. I'm in love with it. It's ridiculous, you know this. But, it's actually serviceable, if you need a small alternative. Will it fit every situation? Maybe not. But it'll most likely fill yours, if you're here. The price is about right, in my humble opinion.

I will be posting a video of my time with it elsewhere, keep an eye out for Havok Versus Everything, or find me just to chat. I will yell about how much I love this thing.

If you have any more questions, ask in the question section and I will answer the best I can. There's too much to say, and a lot of intricacies to owning a phone I might not have thought of off the top of my head. I got ya, just ask.

review_word:
As of January 9, 2021, there are two versions available to rent on Amazon Prime (for the same price):

"The Sword in the Stone (4K UHD)" fills up the screen but has much of the top and/or bottom of the frame chopped off, and it has a warmer color tone. Oddly, it shows a little more of the picture to the left and/or right of the frame.

"The Sword in the Stone" has thick black bars on the left and right of the screen but it shows nearly the entire frame; for example, in a scene at 0:04:30, you can see the ground below Merlin's feet when he's at the well, while in the other version he chopped off at the knees. The color tone is cooler and more like I remember. Both versions are HD.

It seems superfluous to give this classic work a review. The movie is "perfect in every way". In this day and age when many movies hold on to questionable morals "Mary Poppins" stands out as an upbeat story. It teaches the value of the family and seems to focus on the influence of the father in the home and how he can influence his children.

The movie starts out with the theme of the iconic song "Feed the Birds" which teaches Charity, Compassion and Love for our neighbor. The story is nicely paced. Every single song is a classic which will stay with you forever. The superbly choreographed "Step in Time" is delightful.

Don't miss this movie. Their is nothing bad to be said about this movie.

A great follow up movie is "Saving Mr. Banks". It is a delightful "back story" behind the production of the movie "Mary Poppins". It will lift your heart!

Strongly recommended

review: Amazingly music comes back from the dead to be devoured.
review_word:
A (nearly) perfect collection that gathers everything The Zombies recorded during their career. My only complaint is that some of those wonky stereo tracks are missing from this set (and it would have been nice if they could reissue this with properly mastered versions of the remixes that Alec Paleo did).

Their masterpiece “Odessey and Oracle” is included in its entirety along with almost everything else they recorded during their brief, bright career. The mastering and annotation by Alec Paleo is excellent along with great comments from the band members.

The remixed stereo anthology has some nicely done stereo mixes that are balanced better than the original stereo mixes (it’s a separate purchase for those who want to pick it up) and does feature one newly done overdub done for “She’s Not There” (always missing and never done for stereo only mono, this was done directly to the mono mix and never has been on the stereo mix of the song) but, that aside, this makes the perfect compliment to this set.

This is an excellent set well worth picking up. Congrats on making the Rock ‘n’ Roll Hall of Fame guys! (RIP Paul Atkinson and later member Jim Rodford).
The focus is on enjoyment for the family.

Whoever rated the condition of this was probably talking about the physical condition of the warped vinyl, because everything looks wonderful. Whatever the case, it’s a great buy, and I should be able to fix the warp no problem. I’ll happily be rocking out to this for years to come. Solid 8/10, would recommend.

review: This is easily the Most Underrated Disney Movie Ever.
review_word:
As I say, this is easily the Most Underrated Disney Movie Ever. Amidst the devastating wit, uproarious repartee that puts the most renowned full-time live-action comedies to shame, alliterative insults, world-class voice acting (including Disney's greatest all-time voice performance by Peter Ustinov), and an entirely brilliant and unique set of songs by Roger Miller (and Johnny Mercer), there is simply nothing more you could ask for from a movie at all, let alone a Disney movie. This is the finest on-screen depiction of the Robin Hood legend--in fact, Howard Pyle's original should be revised and re-structured to include Sir Hiss, one of the most hilarious characters you'll ever see in animated form. Don't listen to the haters, this is an utterly brilliant film.

Also, Lady Kluck is a total bad*ss.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review: The only machine to consider if you love ice cream
review_word: I’ve made my own ice cream for about 20 years, mainly with a Cuisinart canister style machine and then with a Whynter compressor machine. The difference in performance between those machines and the Lello is like comparing a Ford Pinto to a Ferrari. I read a review that said the Lello was the best, but for the average home user the performance wasn’t so much better to justify the price. I totally disagree with a caveat. I never use more than a 1/2 cup of cream in a quart of ice cream. My guess is that there is a more similar performance from the Cuisinart if you are making a recipe that calls for 2-3 cups of cream, but if you want to make lower fat ice cream without a bunch of fillers or stabilizers, the Lello is the only ice cream maker to consider. The difference in consistency is amazing. If you make a lot of ice cream (the only store bought ice cream I liked went out of business at the beginning of the pandemic, so we make at least 2 quarts of ice cream a week — I have 5 go to flavors that I like to always have on hand) this machine is definitely worth the price. I did pay for the extended warranty, which I never do, because my Whynter machine died a month after the warranty expired and I wanted to make sure I would have this machine for at least 4 years. Besides price, the other reason I initially hesitated on this machine was the non-removable bowl and how hard it would be to clean, but with a sponge it is super easy and a bonus that everything touching your ice cream is stainless steel,
