review: As charming today as when we were kids
review_word:
My wife and I grew up watching Mary Poppins on TV once a year, the GenXers who fell in love with Mary and Bert and the family of Banks. So when Amazon had a nice deal on buying the streaming version, we had to get it. We’ve watched it again and Mary Poppins remains as charming as ever.

If you don’t know the story: The Banks family - father, mother, son and daughter - struggle to understand one another in Edwardian England when women were fighting for the vote and men expected the children to be seen and not heard. As the children drive away each nanny, the children send their wishes out into an ill wind and in flies Mary Poppins. Along with her friend, Bert, Mary will take the children on numerous adventures and help their parents rediscover the joy of life with children. If you’ve never seen it, this is a movie known for it’s charming and memorable songs and moments. Feed the Birds is one of my favorite song (overall) but don’t forget the other fun ones you’ll come away singing forever (think ear worms).

If you’ve never seen it, spend some time with Mary and Bert and the Banks family. And if you have, come back for another visit. If you have kids, sit and watch together and rediscover the joy of time with people you love. It’s charming and sweet and saccharine, and you’ll remember it for a long time to come. Yes, a simpler time, but isn’t that what we all need from time to time...

item: Officemate Heavy Duty Weighted 2-in-1 Tape Dispenser, Recycled,Black (96660)
review: Fits packing tape perfectly. Does NOT fit heat tape or painter's tape perfectly.
review_word:
Second update: after using this with packing tape/scotch tape, I find the cutting bar isn't very good. My packing tape just doesn't cut easily or cleanly. I wish it was sharper. I have to reduce my stars because of it.

Update: after using this for a while with heat tape and packing tape, I got frustrated with it and decided to cancel my second order. I still give the dispenser 5 stars for packing tape and scotch tape. But the cutting edge doesn't work well with heat tape or packing tape. The tape kept falling off the cutting bar. Shoot! Thought I had a great solution for my crafting table, but it's back to the drawing board to find something new. I would still recommend the dispenser for packing tape/scotch tape.

Original review:
I really like this tape dispenser and gave it 5 stars for its intended purpose, which is scotch tape and packing tape. It works perfectly for that application. However; I bought this for a crafting table with the idea that I could have heat tape on the larger side. Unfortunately, the core of heat tape is slightly bigger than packing tape, so it does not fit quite right and rolls around loosely. I also found that painter's tape doesn't fit quite right either. It's a little more snug, but still a bit loose. I decided to keep the dispenser, however, and made a modification to keep the rolls from falling off the sides. I took some electrical tape and cut it lengthwise to make a skinny strip and wound it around the very edge of the dispenser core to build up a lip on the edge - not so much that I couldn't get the roll over the ridge, but enough to keep the heat tape from falling off once installed. The heat tape is very skinny, so there was room leftover and I put painter's tape on the other side of the large core. That one fits better, but does kind of roll around too. I might make a ridge of electrical tape on that side also to keep everything in place. It's possible I could fit a second roll of heat tape on as well, if I make my electrical tape "lip" a little narrower. The nice thing about this setup is that because the rolls don't fit tightly, they move independently of each other, and so this setup functions well. I can pull tape off of either the heat tape or painter's tape, without the other roll moving with it, if that makes sense. The scotch tape side works just fine as is. So now I have 3 different types of tape on my crafting table and I like it! The compartment slot in the dispenser is great to hold weeding tools, scissors, a scoring tool, tweezers, etc. It's a nice addition to my table. I will say that this dispenser is pretty bulky, so make sure you have the space for it. It is heavy, which is great for keeping it in place while you pull the tape. I like this so much that I decided to purchase a second one for my desk and use it for its intended purpose - packing tape and scotch tape. I'll use the compartment slot for pens and pencils.

review: Still wonderful after all these years, and great historical insights!

Though slightly romanticized, this movie is a must-see to understand society (and how it changed) at the end of World War II. Yes, women worked, and - as lifestyle journalists - even bluffed their way through what they wrote. And romance could be a somewhat "musical chairs" experience, as singles suddenly had more opportunities to meet and fall in love.

This is a delightful, feel-good romantic comedy. If you like "White Christmas" (the classic), I think you'll enjoy this, too. I'm not sure it's something to watch every year, year-after-year, but it's worth seeing at least once or twice.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review: 2023Edit: What Ice Cream Dreams are Made Of…why has the price gone up?
review_word:
Edited after a year’s use:
This machine is a mighty beast!!! I bought it to start a small batch gourmet ice cream business and it has not disappointed. My only issue is churning 1 qt at a time is not cost effective. So, I bought the 2qt machine from the same company and it is not remotely as well made as the “Baby Musso” - in fact it is a POS waste od space & money.
I came here to potentially buy another Musso, but it is now $1026 here on Amazon! I paid $620 last year! Meanwhile the machine that is double it’s size has gone down in price. That should tell you everything about the superior Musso! Not sure why the significant difference in performance and function, but as a professional ice cream maker it is shockingly noticeable how bad the larger machine is. I’m here to tell you if you can swing the $1026 go ahead and do it you will not be disappointed!

I had previously purchased the Cuisinart ICE100, it just didn’t get cold enough even with pre chilling the bowl and ice cream base. And if you add commercial stabilizer and/or have a fudgier chocolate base (or cream cheese) the ICE 100 would simply quit. Im I’m an accomplished self taught baker, so I approached ice cream making with an eye for maximum fresh flavors with premium level density. However, it took mishaps with the ICE 100 to bring me around to the Maserati of frisen dessert makers! Hoooo-lah!!! What an epic beauty is this machine!? I had made 4 very dense, richly flavored bases that cured for 48 hours in my fridge. I set the timer to 40 minutes as a guide because the ICE 100 required, well, longer than that. I let the bowl chill up for 4 minutes, added the base (a bit too much! 775ml. I had to stop dasher to remove 100ml), and I swear it was thoroughly done (see photo) in 17 minutes!!!!! I made a second batch of same base directly after scooping out first run and that one finished in roughly 14.5 minutes. I’m blown away. Absolutely worth the investment as I’m planning to launch a mobile scoop shop. I will say the instructions are lacking. I wish they had added some tips on efficient usage when running batches back to back because between the first and second runs I stopped the dasher but not compressor (button with snowflake icon) to add second batch and when I started dasher up the machine made scary noises! I even heard a frying/crackling sound inside and dasher seemed a bit slow yet base was still liquid. Anyone have that happen? I’m running a few more tonight for a client b day party hope it’s ok! 😬 Anyway, so far, so fantastic!

item: Mac Book Pro Charger - 118W USB C Charger Fast Charger for USB C Port MacBook pro/Air, ipad Pro, Samsung Galaxy and All USB C Device, Include Charge Cable（7.2ft/2.2m）
review_word:
I was very surprised when I found this product, which includes the cable for only $30. Originally, I was just looking to replace my factory Apple charging block for my MacBook Pro, and was fully prepared to spend $70 on the block, and up to another $20-30 on the cable. In fact, I went to Best Buy, looking to do just that - but they no longer sold the original Apple product. So, instead, I spent $70 on some off-brand which I didn’t like, for multiple reasons..

First of all, if I’m going to spend that much money, I’m buying the original Apple product; it’s as simple as that. So, I bought the damn thing temporarily, just to have something to use until I could order the Apple one; which, in fact, I was searching for here on Amazon, and surprisingly did not find. That’s how I found this product, instead.

Now, I’m a bit of a review snob. If a product isn’t 4.5+ stars, with a credible amount of reviews, I’m probably not buying it. But, even at this price point, this product was holding a full five stars - so I settled on trying it, instead of going directly to Apple. I love it, honestly. I don’t have any REAL complaints. Just one tiny little thing, that doesn’t really matter. Especially at the end of the day, for this price.

The one that I returned to Best Buy drove me INSANE, because the damn thing was so heavy that it sagged from every outlet you plugged it into. It didn’t feel ANYTHING like the original Apple charger, and it CONSTANTLY fell out of the socket and interrupted my usage experience. Oh, man I cannot tell you how annoying that was.. and I forget why, now but there was something else about the cable, too that just felt nothing like the one I had been using for the last five years. I just, hated it. All around.

This bundle, though is almost exactly the same size as the Apple one, and even a smidge smaller, I think, which is nice. It’s light, as it should be and it actually stays plugged in. That was a pleasant surprise, because at this point I wasn’t sure what to expect. I have no complaints whatsoever about the charging block (which is the expensive part, obviously). I have no use for about half of the power of this thing, since my device only uses a maximum of just over 60 watts, so I can’t attest to an increase in charging speed, or anything like that. But, as a replacement for the factory original device, for even less than half the price, I can say that I am surprisingly pleased.

One of the great things about USB-C and Power Delivery, is that overkill is no problem. It’s not like there’s any worry of pulling too much power, and damaging your device. So, for the fact that this product successfully works as a replacement for my Apple charger, AND includes a free upgrade to upgrade-proof, especially at this price point, is just a really nice added bonus.

The only complaint that I have, is with the cable. It is decently annoying, but it doesn’t bother me because the product overall is such a great value. When plugged in to my MacBook Pro, it will (pretty often, actually) slip out of the USB-C port, justtt enough to disconnect from the device and stop charging. I have to gently snug it back in there, and it only moves this tiny little indeterminate amount. You would never be able to tell, by just looking at it that the connector isn’t fully seated in place, but when you slide it back in, you can feel it move a teeny bit, and you can feel it kind of snap back into place. Again, moderately annoying, but I don’t particularly find this to be a bother, considering I was perfectly willing and prepared to spend 2-3 times the amount of this product on the genuine Apple version. For the value? I really can’t complain.

Plus, if I ever decide that it indeed IS a bother, I could always buy another cable for $20 or less. Hell, I could even buy one straight from Apple, and I’m STILL saving money. So, again, I really can’t complain. For the manufacturer, though: I would definitely recommend replacing the cable that you offer, with this bundle to eliminate this issue. Cables are cheap, and even if you have to raise the price on this bundle accordingly (what, $1.00? $1.50?), it’s worth it to do so. I mean, come on; the charging block itself is a great value, at this price. The cable is just a bonus, anyway.

review: Excellent DVD quality. Funny romantic comedy.
review_word:
The quality of this DVD is excellent. The colors are just as vibrant as they originally were on the big screen, and the audio is loud and clear. Letterbox shows the panorama of the breathtaking Italian countryside. English subtitles are available and easy to activate.

As for the movie itself, Elizabeth Taylor and Richard Burton did give wonderful performances. Burton, in particular, was in his comfort zone because his strong resume consisted of successfully playing many Shakespearean roles live on the stage in England. As a result, he portrayed the loud, obnoxious character of Petruchio brilliantly. Taylor, who had never performed as a Shakespearan character, was not so self-confident in her role as the ill-tempered and aggressive (aka shrewish) Katharina, but director Franco Zeffirelli was very pleased with her performance. item: A Goofy Movie (Walt Disney Gold Classic Collection) [VHS]
review_word: Oldie and goody

>> This review does not contain spoilers or a synopsis of the movie.

If you enjoy psychological horror/thrillers and adult-oriented anime, this cult classic is for you! This animated movie was created by the legendary artist, the late Satoshi Kon (rest-in-peace). Satoshi Kon is best known for pioneering mind-blowing transitions and reality-warping storytelling in the anime genre and this movie is the perfect representation. Perfect Blue is the predecessor Kon’s other famous works such as the movie Paprika and the TV series Paranoia Agent, which I also recommend watching.

The only reason I would not recommend this film is if you are uncomfortable with depictions of r-a-p-e, uncensored m-u-r-d-e-r, and female n-u-d-i-t-y. As such, this anime film contains adult themes and a dark, twisted storyline that should only be seen by those who are over the age of 18. Perfect Blue is not an offensive or grotesque anime by any means, but the sensitive topics that are displayed should not be viewed by children.

Most Asian films and shows include the English subtitled version with the original language and sometimes an English adaptation if the work becomes popular amongst Westerners, but weirdly enough this somewhat obscure, Japanese anime only contains the English adaptation. I do not remember seeing any options in the menu to select versions that contain the original Japanese voice-acting with/without subtitles. If you prefer “dubs” over “subs”, then you are in luck!

>> TLDR; Must-watch if you are a “sophisticated” anime connoisseur. Rated R for anime tiddies.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review_word:
I bought this from Amazon in February 2003, and thought it was about time to testify to its durability.

I've made hundreds of batches of ice cream over the past nearly 20 years with it. I have never had it serviced.

In the early days, I was worried that the paddle was looking a little oxidized, so I contacted the manufacturer, and they cheerfully (seriously) sent me another, no problem. I kept both, and it turns out that my concern was exaggerated, and it was just a little discolored.

I got a couple of scares with it in the last couple of years. Twice, the churn motor wouldn't turn, even with no resistance, and I thought it had met its demise; however, rumors of its death were greatly exaggerated. It just needed to cool down thoroughly, and it ran again. I don't understand how it still chills like it did in 2003.

When I got it, my daughter had just turned 9, and would spend some of her summers with me. It was a great way to entertain her and give her a break from my otherwise healthy-food obsession. She's now 26 and still wonders at the fact that I've still got this thing. Now I've got another batch of kids 9, 8, and 6, and they're enjoying it just like their much older sister did.

There's a quirk about this machine in the manual. This was advertised as an Italian ice cream maker (and it is made in Italy), but the manual says about its name: "Lussino is the name of a beautiful island off the Istria Peninsula and the Dalmatian Coast. At the present time Lussino Island is under the Republic of Croatia, but it is part of the Italian Nation for tradition, heritage, language, and historical links."

review: A flawed reimagining of Heat in 4K.
review_word:
Mann went to town on the 2017 remaster, and this one goes even further into dimness and warmth. I can't quite understand why he is doing this to the film, but it is what it is. I guess he really wanted a more LA warm look everything.

Within this questionable color timing, which is vastly different than the blue and sometimes teal 2009 release, Heat 4K looks orange-tinted with yellows filtered into the mix, making even more teal highlights with the blues, but with the strangeness that such a warm transfer imparts. I can kind of see his intent, but this doesn't really give one a totally professional remix.

Problem is Disney cheaped out on this release as they don't seem to much care about some of the studios they acquire. This is a BD66 for a three hour film. There is no Dolby Vision, the slipcover sucks, and the HDR grade is basically barely even there. Atmos you wish.

I just can't quite wrap my head around Mann's tinkering anymore. When did he suddenly hate the bluer original? Even the marketing was in blue.

KEEP your 2009 disc. It's a fine disc even on the old VC-1 encoder, and it looks way more like the film I saw in theaters. This is something different entirely. To call this definitive is probably not quite accurate considering everything this current version is missing. No Atmos might be the biggest sin.

Match that with a photoshop dive job of a cover, and this release is just not very good. They could have done so much better, and we deserve better. The steelbook looks much nicer, but it's also super limited. And for those that care there is an overseas AVC-coded release of Heat with higher bitrate than the OG 2009 version, both being of the same master and color timing.

I really hope someday Heat will get a more authentic release. Until then you can get this one and see a more warmly colored version of this classic, or you can find the 2009 version on bluray for a presentation closer to the original.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review_word:
I've had a few different ice cream makers with the removable bowl that you toss in the freezer. I've had a few disasters, too. These occur when the maker runs out of cold before the ice cream runs out of heat, usually because I've altered the recipe in some fashion. One of these occasions arose a couple days ago: 20 minutes had elapsed, the temperature of the mix was down to 28°, and yet there was no indication it was ready to freeze.

This particular recipe of mine variation took another 25 minutes with a drop to 24° before, blessedly, ice cream appeared. Instead of the mix going down the drain after it failed to freeze in time, it went on to become a family favorite.

I had always assumed the only real advantage of a refrigerated ice cream maker is that you get the better part of a cubic foot back in your freezer. The bigger advantage is that you'll never find yourself pouring a new ice cream mix down the drain.

Oh, and the Musso Lussin is built like a tank yet is half as wide as the competition. True, it's twice as deep, but its prominent rear end slipped back beneath a cabinet in our kitchen into what would otherwise be dead space. That was my main reason for picking it out until I read the reviews and discovered that it also happens to be the best on the market.

review: Great movie, but the 4k release is really dark
review_word:
I was really looking forward to the 4k release of this movie for months and since pre-ordering Dune earlier this year, it's been the only other movie I payed for early. I have to say that I'm a little bit disappointed in the 4k print of Heat. It is true that most of the movie has never looked better. The day scenes especially look amazing - including the bank heist scene, which is just perfect. The problems come whenever there is a scene set at night... and there are kind of a lot of them in this movie. Details are lost in the shadows of the scene and unless they are directly in a source of light, characters pretty much disappear from sight. I basically had to double check if my settings got changed before watching this movie, but they didn't. I'm using the same settings that I pre-configured for every other movie I have watched. I had to crank up the brightness and switch to Vivid mode on my LG C1 just to be able to see anything. Hopefully you can tell in the pictures I took. It wasn't easy replicating what I see on screen through pictures, but I think they do a decent job. As you can tell though, whenever you have to raise the brightness that much, the blacks turn grey and it makes my OLED look not as good.

So yeah, if I'm scoring just the film it would get a 5/5. It still holds up really well even though it's been 27 years since the original release. But if I'm scoring the entire experience of the 4k Blu Ray print, I can't give it more than 3/5 stars.

item: Lello 4080 Musso Lussino 1.5-Quart Ice Cream Maker, Stainless - 110/120V 60 HZ
review_word:
if you are even THINKING about buying an ice cream maker, this is the one to buy. Yes it costs more than the others, but it is SO worth it.

I've had other machines where you have to pre freeze a bowl and then add your ingredients. The ice cream was never fully frozen and more than one batch was out of the question. Plus the bowls were always flimsy and easily damaged by taking the ice cream out of the bowl.

With this machine, there is no bowl. Turn the machine on and let it get cool, then add your ice cream mix (goes even faster if you chill it first) and pour it into the machine. 15 minutes later you have the best home made ice cream, gelato, or sorbet you've ever had.

Yes, there is some noise. But not any more than any other ice cream machine. And I thought it would be difficult to clean with an integrated hbowl, but you simply scoop out your ice cream with a spatula, (which gets it pretty clean as there are no seams or corners to deal with ) and then use a damp sponge to clean out any remaining ice cream.

The convenience of not have to pre-freeze or worry about puncturing a bowl in the cheaper models is worth the extra money. But add in the all-metal construction, a sturdy as hell motor, and the ability to keep making more ice cream after one or two batches, and this machine is more than worth the premium price.

My ONLY minor complaint is that I wish it had a better way to store the cord, which comes from underneath the unit. But a small cord winder stuck to the side took care of that.

This is one AWESOME machine.

After a successful robbery of a gang of Chinese henchmen, gunman Porter is betrayed and shot and left for dead. And that's only the beginning...After his recovery, Porter looks for revenge, and his share of the loot: $70,000. "Payback(1999)" is a rollicking good-time, if you like violence, pretty girls, and Mel Gibson. And here is Gibson at his finest. First-time director Brian Helgeland sports an uncanny flair for Hollywood smaltch, and he ain't afraid to show it. Helping out is a sound supporting cast, including Maria Bello as his girlfriend(Porter's wife dies early in the film from a Heroin overdose.). Also along for the ride is Gregg Henry, as Val Resnick, a Mafia connection(There are several). Among the devious reprobates are Lucy Liu, Kris Kristofferson, James Coburn(very good), and a delicious performance by William Devane as Carter. Devane licks his lips, pulls on his $10,000 suit, and oozes evil. Porter manages to get shot, beat-up, and tortured in one scene after another. What a guy? A pawn shop provides him with a Smith and Wesson Model 27 .357 Magnum with a four-inch barrel and custom wood grips. Late in the party, one gangster home is filmed at the Doheny Mansion , on Mount St. Mary's College, 10 Chester Place, Los Angeles.

Molly Hatchet appeared in the late summer of 1978 just in time to help Southern Rock fans get over their mourning over the loss of Lynyrd Skynyrd and the awful plane crash. Molly Hatchet was also from the same Jacksonville scene and no doubt rubbed shoulders with Van Zandt and co. during their formative years. A sextet rather than a septet (no piano player ala Billy Powell), Hatchet roared out of the box with a stunning debut that seemed to both pay tribute to their forebears (witness their stunning cover of the Allman’s “Dreams I’ll Never See) but also seemed to say that they had come to claim Skynyrd’s title as the top dog in Southern Rock (subtle put downs of where the other bands originally came from on the second track “Gator Country”). The LP opens with a band as “Bounty Hunter ''roars out of the gates ferociously announcing Molly Hatchet’s arrival and demonstating the barrelhouse pipes of singer and Ronnie sound alike Danny Joe Brown. Other key tracks include the aforementioned “Gator Country” (featuring a typical guitar workout outro) and “Dreams” in which Molly Hatchet radically reinterpret the Allman Brothers classic so that it sounds like an original. “The Creeper”, “Cheatin’ Woman” and “Big Apple” dish out steaming Southern hospitality and immediately endear the listener whether good ole boy or a Yankee like me. While it was immediately overshadowed by the follow-up ‘Flirtin’ with Disaster’ (the title track alone would forever define this band), I don’t think Molly Hatchet made a better record (other than ‘Flirtin’) after their first. Line-up changes would soon bedevil the band as Brown would soon leave after album 2 (though they maintain some momentum as ‘Beating the Odds’ also went mult-platinum) but it would not last much into the 1980’s. Molly Hatchet, much like fellow Jacksonville brethren Blackfoot, would compete rather proudly with the hard rock/heavy metal acts of their era and bring a heavier edge to Southern Rock. New York City you’re so big and tough? Not to these guys.
Need I say more ... WHOOP WHOOP!!

review: The rare case where the censored version is arguably better?
review_word:
This headbending, ahead-of-its-time Hitchcockian thriller follows an actress whose attempt to break away from girl-group stardom to forge a more serious acting career goes frighteningly wrong. Soon, her sanity's fraying as she's stalked both by a real-world obsessive and, seemingly, by a mocking phantom version of the bright, cheerful stage persona she left behind. As her breakdown intensifies, director Satoshi Kon blurs reality and cinematic fiction in increasingly clever and unsettling ways, leading to a thrilling, reality-warping final chase sequence that takes full advantage of animation's power to tell stories in ways live action simply can't. Made at the dawn of the Internet age, the film's keen attention to all the ways the Web could be turned against women seems creepily prescient.

Unfortunately, that's not the only creepiness going on here. When I first saw this film about 20 years ago on DVD, I didn't realize I was watching a censored, R-rated version. The cuts made to get that rating -- primarily to the more graphic images in a murder sequence, a scene where the heroine's being pressured to take photographs with which she's not comfortable, and a final scene where someone's attempting to assault her -- didn't rob the film of any of its eerie power. And by suggesting, rather than showing, the grimier aspects of the narrative, they increased your sympathy for its heroine. (There's even some brilliantly deployed, near-subliminal fast cuts in the censored version, leaving you wondering whether you actually just saw what you thought you did -- which ties in really well to the film's overall theme!) The R-rated version critiques the heroine's exploitation without participating in it.

That version, alas, isn't even an option on this edition, which came as an unpleasant surprise to me. The original cut gets graphic in ways that feel like it's taking part in leering at its heroine, rather than siding with her. Maybe the filmmakers were trying to make you complicit in that process, but doing so makes the viewing process deeply, viscerally unpleasant in ways that seem to go far beyond any kind of artistic intent.

When those seedier aspects aren't shoved in your face, the film is brilliant -- a borderline masterpiece. I'd have no qualms rewatching and appreciating the R-rated cut for years to come. But the uncut original version's lack of restraint works against it, and leaves me uncertain about whether I'll ever feel up to watching it again.

If you want to give Kon's work a try -- and if you love movies, you absolutely should -- start instead with MILLENNIUM ACTRESS or especially TOKYO GODFATHERS, which harness all his considerable talents toward kinder, more humanist ends that a wider audience can enjoy.

item: Motorola Moto G Stylus | 2023 | Unlocked | Made for US 4/64GB | 50 MP Camera | Glam Pink, 162.89 x 74.08 x 9.19mm
review: Good for the price! Don't let negative reviews scare you off.
review_word:
Overall the Moto G Pure is a good phone for the money.

I do not play games or take a lot of photos. I do not have a lot of apps installed either. I use the phone for calls, texts, navigation, browsing the interwebs, and using a few apps (amazon, ebay, offer up, banking, health care). For these purposes, the phone is more than adequate. I am VERY happy with the purchase. I was going to use this phone as a temp phone until the new iPhone SE reviews came out. I like the G Pure so much that I might just keep it long term. So, if you have a similar use case, then do not be scared of the reviews showing horrible geekbench scores for the MediaTek Helios processor. Also, the near stock Android experience with no bloatware is refreshing. I like the little moto tweaks, like chopping twice for the flashlight.

However, there are some caveats:

There is no 5G and no NFC. So no google pay (do you trust google?). The lack of 5G is not a deal breaker for me as my carrier charges extra for 5G anyways.

The face unlock is unreliable (boo). I do not take selfies, so it could very well be that I am holding the phone incorrectly when trying to unlock the phone. However, I feel like an idiot moving the phone around trying to get the phone to unlock with facial recognition until the phone gives up and begs me to use fingerprint or PIN unlock. I was really hoping this feature was going to make me feel like I have a cheap iPhone. I was mistaken. This is not a deal breaker, but it is a let down.

The storage is a pitiful 32 GB. The OS alone with the preinstalled google aps uses about half of that. So if you have/need lots of apps look elsewhere. My previous 2017 phone also had the same amount of storage but more carrier bloatware. Still, the 32 GB feels cramped for me and will definitely feel cramped for most people.

The OS is android 11. This is already one version behind the current android 12 (at the date of purchase Feb. 2020), but the G Pure is supposed to get updated to android 12 and then that's probably it. This is the reason that I chose the G Pure over the G Play. The G Play has a bigger battery and a more commonly targeted Qualcomm processor. But the G Play has android 10 and will only get updated to android 11. Why does Motorola makes such good phones and have such a horrible update policy? If any Motorola bots are reading this, please note that I would buy a more expensive Motorola phone AND recommend Motorola to others if this were not the case. As it stands, I expect every Motorola phone purchase to result in being abandoned before you even get your new phone in the mail.

I know that there are more "cons" listed than "pluses", but I think some of the "cons" would be deal breakers for a lot of people. BUT, overall I am VERY happy with the purchase for my use case and expect to sue the phone for quite some time at the moment. So if you have similar needs, then you should expect to be happy as well.

Heat is a movie that you can rewatch time and time again. Its grounded setting in the city of LA is the backdrop of characters that are larger than life, each in their own ways. Al Pacino and Robert De Niro put on stunning performances, each at the peak of their careers (in my opinion), and the first scene they share is one of the most brilliant scenes in film, one I rewatch frequently. Matter of fact, I’m watching it right after I write this review. Watch this movie, witness Mann’s vision, experience the gripping action, listen to the surreal soundtrack, and have a great time.

On the BluRay, it’s a good version. It gets the job done.
